{
  "The nucleus of an atom contains:": "",
  "Protons and electrons": "",
  "Only protons": "",
  "Protons and neutrons": "",
  "Neutrons and electrons": "",
  "The atomic nucleus consists of protons (positive charge) and neutrons (neutral). Together they are called nucleons and are held together by the strong nuclear force.": "",
  "Alpha decay produces:": "",
  "A neutron without accounting": "",
  "An electron when considering all": "",
  "A photon, as conventional alpha theory": "",
  "A helium-4 nucleus (2 protons and 2 neutrons)": "",
  "In alpha decay, the nucleus emits an alpha particle (helium-4 nucleus: 2 protons + 2 neutrons). The parent nucleus loses 2 protons and 2 neutrons, reducing its atomic number by 2 and mass number by 4.": "",
  "Beta-minus decay involves the emission of:": "",
  "A gamma ray": "",
  "A positron": "",
  "An alpha particle": "",
  "An electron and an antineutrino": "",
  "In beta-minus decay, a neutron converts to a proton, emitting an electron (beta particle) and an antineutrino. The atomic number increases by 1 while the mass number stays the same.": "",
  "Gamma radiation is:": "",
  "A stream of neutrons": "",
  "A stream of electrons": "",
  "High-energy electromagnetic radiation (photons)": "",
  "A stream of helium nuclei": "",
  "Gamma radiation consists of high-energy photons emitted from excited nuclei. It has no charge or mass and does not change the atomic number or mass number of the nucleus.": "",
  "The half-life of a radioactive isotope is the time for:": "",
  "All atoms to decay": "",
  "The radiation to become safe": "",
  "Half the radioactive atoms to decay": "",
  "One atom to decay": "",
  "The half-life (t_1/2) is the time required for half of the radioactive nuclei in a sample to undergo radioactive decay. After n half-lives, the fraction remaining is (1/2)^n.": "",
  "Which type of radiation has the highest penetrating power?": "",
  "Alpha": "",
  "Beta": "",
  "Gamma": "",
  "All are equally penetrating": "",
  "Gamma rays are the most penetrating: they can pass through the body and require thick lead or concrete to stop. Alpha is stopped by paper, beta by a few mm of aluminum.": "",
  "The strong nuclear force holds nucleons together and is:": "",
  "Weaker than the electromagnetic force": "",
  "Only attractive to protons": "",
  "Infinite in range": "",
  "Stronger than the electromagnetic force but very short-range": "",
  "The strong nuclear force is the strongest fundamental force but acts only at very short distances (about 10^-15 m). It binds protons and neutrons in the nucleus, overcoming the electromagnetic repulsion between protons.": "",
  "Mass-energy equivalence (E = mc^2) in nuclear reactions means that:": "",
  "Mass is always conserved": "",
  "A small amount of mass can be converted into a large amount of energy": "",
  "Mass and energy are unrelated": "",
  "Energy cannot be created from mass": "",
  "Einstein's E = mc^2 shows that mass and energy are interchangeable. In nuclear reactions, a small mass deficit (difference between reactant and product masses) is converted to a large amount of energy.": "",
  "Nuclear fission is the process of:": "",
  "Combining small nuclei to form a larger nucleus": "",
  "Splitting a heavy nucleus into lighter nuclei, releasing energy": "",
  "Converting protons to neutrons": "",
  "Emitting alpha particles": "",
  "Nuclear fission occurs when a heavy nucleus (like U-235) splits into two lighter nuclei plus neutrons, releasing a large amount of energy. This is the basis of nuclear power plants and atomic weapons.": "",
  "Nuclear fusion is the process that powers:": "",
  "Radioactive decay": "",
  "The Sun and other stars": "",
  "Nuclear power plants": "",
  "Chemical batteries": "",
  "Nuclear fusion - combining light nuclei (like hydrogen) into heavier nuclei (like helium) - powers the Sun and stars. It releases enormous energy because the products have less mass than the reactants.": "",
  "What is radioactivity?": "",
  "The reflection of nuclear energy according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The emission of radio waves by atoms within the broader context of particles analysis": "",
  "The spontaneous emission of particles or energy from unstable atomic nuclei as they transform into more stable configurations": "",
  "The absorption of radiation by materials, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Radioactivity is the spontaneous disintegration of unstable atomic nuclei, emitting alpha particles, beta particles, gamma rays, or other radiation. The process transforms the nucleus into a different, more stable configuration.": "",
  "What is half-life?": "",
  "The time for radiation to travel half a distance under most circumstances involving half": "",
  "The time required for half of the radioactive nuclei in a sample to undergo decay, a constant characteristic of each radioactive isotope": "",
  "50% of the decay energy when the interaction between half and life factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Half the lifetime of a radioactive atom, particularly in the context of half": "",
  "Half-life (t_1/2) is the time for exactly half the atoms in a radioactive sample to decay. It is constant for each isotope and ranges from fractions of a second to billions of years.": "",
  "What is alpha decay?": "",
  "The emission of a photon from a nucleus, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A radioactive process where a nucleus emits a helium-4 nucleus (alpha particle), reducing its atomic number by 2 and mass number by 4": "",
  "The splitting of a nucleus into two equal parts without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The capture of an electron by a nucleus, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "In alpha decay, a heavy nucleus ejects an alpha particle (He-4: 2p + 2n). Example: U-238 -> Th-234 + He-4. The parent atom loses 2 from its atomic number and 4 from its mass number.": "",
  "What is beta decay?": "",
  "The emission of gamma radiation, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Nuclear fission, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual beta mechanisms at work": "",
  "The emission of a helium nucleus, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "A nuclear process where a neutron converts to a proton (or vice versa), emitting an electron or positron and a neutrino": "",
  "Beta decay involves the weak nuclear force: in beta-minus, a neutron becomes a proton + electron + antineutrino; in beta-plus, a proton becomes a neutron + positron + neutrino. The mass number stays constant.": "",
  "What is nuclear binding energy?": "",
  "The energy released in chemical reactions": "",
  "The kinetic energy of nuclear particles": "",
  "The energy needed to ionize an atom": "",
  "The energy required to completely separate all nucleons in a nucleus, equivalent to the mass defect times c^2": "",
  "Nuclear binding energy is the energy needed to disassemble a nucleus into individual protons and neutrons. It equals the mass defect (difference between separate nucleon masses and actual nuclear mass) times c^2.": "",
  "What is mass defect?": "",
  "An error in measuring atomic mass because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "The mass of emitted radiation, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual mass mechanisms at work": "",
  "The difference between the sum of individual nucleon masses and the actual mass of the nucleus, representing mass converted to binding energy": "",
  "The mass lost during chemical reactions, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Mass defect (delta_m) is the 'missing mass' of a nucleus: the combined mass of separated nucleons minus the actual nuclear mass. This mass is converted to binding energy: E_b = delta_m * c^2.": "",
  "What is nuclear fission?": "",
  "The combining of light nuclei, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing fission dynamics": "",
  "The decay of a free neutron based on the conventional understanding of how fission processes interact in practice": "",
  "The emission of an alpha particle, particularly when fission considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy nucleus (typically after absorbing a neutron) into two medium-mass nuclei plus neutrons, releasing large amounts of energy": "",
  "Nuclear fission occurs when a heavy nucleus (like U-235 or Pu-239) splits into two lighter nuclei after absorbing a neutron. The process releases ~200 MeV per event and additional neutrons that can sustain a chain reaction.": "",
  "What is nuclear fusion?": "",
  "The splitting of heavy nuclei considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "The absorption of neutrons by heavy nuclei according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The combining of light nuclei to form a heavier nucleus, releasing energy because the product has higher binding energy per nucleon": "",
  "The radioactive decay of unstable isotopes, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Nuclear fusion combines light nuclei (like hydrogen isotopes) into heavier ones (like helium), releasing energy. It requires extremely high temperatures (~10^7 K) to overcome electrostatic repulsion, as in stellar cores.": "",
  "What is the decay constant?": "",
  "The energy released per decay under most circumstances involving lambda": "",
  "The total activity of a sample, as conventional lambda theory would suggest": "",
  "The number of decays per atom when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The probability per unit time that a given nucleus will decay, related to half-life by lambda = ln(2)/t_1/2": "",
  "The decay constant (lambda) is the probability per unit time of a nucleus decaying: N(t) = N0*e^(-lambda*t). It relates to half-life: lambda = ln(2)/t_1/2 = 0.693/t_1/2.": "",
  "What is the strong nuclear force?": "",
  "The force responsible for beta decay, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual strong mechanisms at work": "",
  "Gravity at the atomic scale considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "The fundamental force that binds protons and neutrons together in the nucleus, overcoming electromagnetic repulsion at very short ranges (~10^-15 m)": "",
  "The force that holds electrons in atoms, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual strong mechanisms at work": "",
  "The strong nuclear force (strong interaction) is the strongest of the four fundamental forces. It binds quarks together and, in its residual form, holds protons and neutrons in the nucleus. It only acts over ~10^-15 m.": "",
  "Carbon-14 has a half-life of 5,730 years. An archaeological sample has 1/8 of the original C-14 remaining. How old is the sample?": "",
  "22,920 years": "",
  "5,730 years": "",
  "11,460 years": "",
  "17,190 years": "",
  "1/8 = (1/2)^3, so 3 half-lives have passed. Age = 3 * 5,730 = 17,190 years.": "",
  "Uranium-238 undergoes alpha decay. What is the daughter nucleus?": "",
  "Radium-234": "",
  "Uranium-234": "",
  "Plutonium-242": "",
  "Thorium-234": "",
  "U-238 -> Th-234 + He-4. Alpha decay reduces the atomic number by 2 (92 -> 90 = Thorium) and mass number by 4 (238 -> 234).": "",
  "The binding energy per nucleon is highest for which element?": "",
  "Hydrogen": "",
  "Uranium": "",
  "Iron (Fe-56)": "",
  "Helium": "",
  "Iron-56 (and nearby nuclei like Ni-62) have the highest binding energy per nucleon (~8.8 MeV). This is why both fission of heavy nuclei and fusion of light nuclei release energy - both move toward iron on the binding energy curve.": "",
  "A radioactive sample has an initial activity of 800 Bq. After 3 half-lives, the activity is:": "",
  "100 Bq": "",
  "50 Bq": "",
  "400 Bq": "",
  "200 Bq": "",
  "After each half-life, the activity halves. After 3 half-lives: 800 * (1/2)^3 = 800/8 = 100 Bq.": "",
  "In the fusion reaction 2H + 3H -> 4He + n, the mass of the reactants is 5.03018 u and the products have a mass of 5.01141 u. How much energy is released? (1 u = 931.5 MeV/c^2)": "",
  "17.6 MeV": "",
  "1.76 MeV": "",
  "0.176 MeV": "",
  "176 MeV": "",
  "Mass defect = 5.03018 - 5.01141 = 0.01877 u. Energy = 0.01877 * 931.5 = 17.49 MeV ≈ 17.6 MeV.": "",
  "A nuclear medicine technician administers Iodine-131 (half-life = 8 days) to a patient. After 24 days, what fraction of the original dose remains?": "",
  "1/2": "",
  "1/4": "",
  "1/8": "",
  "1/16": "",
  "Number of half-lives = 24/8 = 3. Fraction remaining = (1/2)^3 = 1/8.": "",
  "A Geiger counter near a radioactive source reads 1200 counts per minute. The source has a half-life of 2 hours. What will the reading be after 6 hours?": "",
  "300 cpm": "",
  "75 cpm": "",
  "600 cpm": "",
  "150 cpm": "",
  "Number of half-lives = 6/2 = 3. Activity = 1200 * (1/2)^3 = 1200/8 = 150 counts per minute.": "",
  "Cobalt-60 undergoes beta-minus decay. Write the decay equation and identify the daughter nucleus.": "",
  "Copper-60": "",
  "Manganese-60": "",
  "Iron-60": "",
  "Nickel-60": "",
  "Co-60 -> Ni-60 + e- + antineutrino. Beta-minus decay increases the atomic number by 1 (27 -> 28 = Nickel) while the mass number stays at 60.": "",
  "A nuclear power plant uses U-235 fission. Each fission releases about 200 MeV. If the plant generates 1000 MW of thermal power, how many fissions per second are needed?": "",
  "3.1 * 10^19": "",
  "5.0 * 10^21": "",
  "3.1 * 10^22": "",
  "3.1 * 10^16": "",
  "200 MeV = 200 * 1.6e-13 J = 3.2e-11 J per fission. N = P/E = 10^9/(3.2e-11) = 3.125 * 10^19 fissions per second.": "",
  "A PET scan uses Fluorine-18 (half-life = 110 min). A dose of 10 mCi is prepared at 8:00 AM but the scan doesn't start until 11:40 AM. What is the activity at the time of the scan?": "",
  "1.25 mCi": "",
  "2.5 mCi": "",
  "3.5 mCi": "",
  "5.0 mCi": "",
  "Time elapsed = 3 hours 40 min = 220 min. Number of half-lives = 220/110 = 2. Activity = 10 * (1/2)^2 = 10/4 = 2.5 mCi.": ""
